    <h1>History & Empire Overview</h1>
    <p>Vijayanagara, the "City of Victory," served as the capital of the illustrious Vijayanagara Empire from 1336 to 1565 CE. Founded by Harihara I and Bukka Raya of the Sangama dynasty, it grew into one of the world’s largest medieval cities—second only to Beijing—with an estimated population of ~500,000 by 1500 CE :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}.</p>
    <p>The empire was a bastion of Hindu rule in South India, fiercely resisting northern invasions for over two centuries. It reached its zenith under Krishnadevaraya (1509–29), achieving military, administrative, and cultural heights :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}.</p>

    <h1>Architecture & Monumental Sites</h1>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Virupaksha Temple</strong>: A 7th‑century shrine dedicated to Lord Shiva, continuously in worship and surrounded by the famed ruins of Hampi :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}.</li>
      <li><strong>Vittala Temple Complex</strong>: Renowned for its iconic stone chariot and resonant musical pillars—a hallmark of Vijayanagara architecture :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}.</li>
      <li><strong>Lotus Mahal & Elephant Stables</strong>: Reflecting Indo‑Persian and Deccan aesthetic influences in secular palace architecture :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}.</li>
      <li><strong>Hazara‑Rama & Kodandarama Temples</strong>: Royal temples noted for elaborate relief work depicting scenes from Ramayana and Mahabharata :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}.</li>
    </ul>

    <h1>Cultural & Artistic Legacy</h1>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Vijayanagara Style</strong>: A syncretic fusion of Chalukya, Hoysala, Pandya, and Chola traditions, featuring grand gopurams, pillared mandapas, and intricate granite carvings :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}.</li>
      <li><strong>Painting & Sculpture</strong>: Frescoes in temples like Virupaksha, along with a distinct architectural sculpture style that influenced later Mysore and Tanjore schools :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}.</li>
      <li><strong>Literature & Music</strong>: A flourishing multilingual literary tradition in Kannada, Telugu, Tamil and Sanskrit, stimulated by royal patronage. Also, Carnatic music in its current form took shape during this era :contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}.</li>
    </ul>

