    <h1>Empire & Administration</h1>
    <p>Vijayanagara featured a quasi‑federal system where provinces were governed by royal princes and nobility, maintaining their armies and courts while paying tribute to the central authority :contentReference[oaicite:11]{index=11}. The economy was advanced, with strong agriculture, mining, textiles, trade (both inland and overseas), and guild-regulated industries :contentReference[oaicite:12]{index=12}.</p>

    <h1>Decline & Declared Heritage</h1>
    <p>The empire declined sharply after the Battle of Talikota in 1565, when combined armies of the Deccan Sultanates defeated Vijayanagara, leading to the capital’s destruction. Successor dynasties moved capitals to Penukonda and Chandragiri until the empire fully dissolved by the mid-17th century :contentReference[oaicite:13]{index=13}.</p>
    <p>Today, the UNESCO-listed Group of Monuments at Hampi stand as a window into the grandeur and influence of the Vijayanagara Empire :contentReference[oaicite:14]{index=14}.</p>

    <h1>Visitor Planning</h1>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Best Time to Visit:</strong> October–March, when weather is pleasant for exploring ruins.</li>
      <li><strong>Access:</strong> Nearest airport & major railhead: Hospet (Hosapete), ~13 km away. Good road connectivity from Hospet and Bangalore.</li>
      <li><strong>Stay Options:</strong> A range from guesthouses and riverside homestays in Hampi Bazaar to resorts near Hospet.</li>
      <li><strong>Tour Tip:</strong> Rent a bicycle or moped to tour the spread-out ruins; a two-day itinerary covers main monuments comfortably.</li>
    </ul>
    
    
